# Form Design

Forms are where users give information to the system. They are the highest-friction interaction pattern in any interface. Every unnecessary field, unclear label, or confusing validation message directly reduces completion rates.

## Core Principles

- **Ask only what you need.** Every field should have a reason. If you can derive or default a value, do so
- **Make the path obvious.** Users should understand what to fill in, in what order, and what happens when they submit
- **Prevent errors over punishing them.** Constraints, defaults, and smart input types catch problems before they start
- **Respect the user's effort.** Never clear a form on error. Never lose data on navigation. Never ask for information you already have (WCAG 3.3.7)

## Labels

- **Every input must have a visible `<label>`** — programmatically associated via `for` / `id`
- Labels go **above the input** for most layouts (fastest scan pattern) or to the left for dense, data-entry forms
- Never use placeholder text as a label — it disappears on focus, fails contrast requirements, and confuses screen readers
- Placeholder text is for **format hints**: "e.g., jane@example.com" or "MM/DD/YYYY"
- Mark optional fields (not required fields) — most fields in a well-designed form are required, so "Optional" labels are less noisy than asterisks everywhere

## Input Types

Use the most specific HTML input type available — it triggers the correct mobile keyboard, enables browser autofill, and provides native validation:

| Data | Input type | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Email | `type="email"` | Shows @ keyboard, validates format |
| Phone | `type="tel"` | Shows numeric keyboard |
| URL | `type="url"` | Shows / and .com keyboard |
| Number | `type="number"` or `inputmode="numeric"` | Shows number pad; use `inputmode` for numbers that aren't quantities (zip codes, IDs) |
| Date | `type="date"` | Native date picker |
| Search | `type="search"` | Shows search keyboard, clear button |
| Password | `type="password"` | Masked input; add a show/hide toggle |

- Use `<select>` for 4–15 fixed options; use radio buttons for 2–5 options where comparison matters
- Use checkboxes for independent boolean choices; never for mutually exclusive options
- Use `<textarea>` for multi-line free text with a visible resize handle
- Autocomplete/typeahead for large option sets (hundreds of items)

## Autofill & Autocomplete

- Set `autocomplete` attributes on all standard fields (`name`, `email`, `tel`, `address-line1`, etc.)
- Never disable browser autofill unless there's a security-critical reason (and even then, reconsider)
- Allow password managers to fill credentials (WCAG 3.3.8) — never block paste in password fields

## Validation & Error Handling

### Timing
- Validate **on blur** (when the user leaves a field) — not on every keystroke
- Re-validate **on input** after an error has been shown (so the error clears as soon as the user fixes it)
- Server-side validation on submit is always the final check — client-side validation is a convenience, not a guarantee

### Error message anatomy
1. **What's wrong:** "Email address is missing"
2. **How to fix it:** "Enter your email address"
3. **Example (if helpful):** "(e.g., jane@example.com)"

### Error display
- Show errors **directly below the field** they relate to
- Use `aria-describedby` to associate the error with its input for screen readers
- Use `aria-invalid="true"` on the input when an error is active
- Use a consistent error color (typically red, `--color-error`) with an icon — never color alone
- On submit with errors: focus the first invalid field and scroll it into view
- Show a summary of errors at the top of the form for forms with many fields

### What not to do
- Don't validate while the user is still typing (it feels combative)
- Don't clear the form on error — preserve all entered data
- Don't show errors for fields the user hasn't interacted with yet
- Don't use toast notifications for form errors — errors must be visible next to their fields
- Don't use only color to indicate errors (see accessibility rule)

## Layout

- **One column** for most forms — it has the fastest completion time and lowest error rate
- Two-column forms are acceptable only for short, related field pairs (First name / Last name, City / State)
- Group related fields with `<fieldset>` and `<legend>` — screen readers announce the group context
- Logical tab order: top-to-bottom, left-to-right. The DOM order should match the visual order
- Visual grouping: add more space between groups than between fields within a group (Gestalt proximity)

## Buttons

- **Primary submit button** should be visually prominent and labeled with the specific action: "Add Student," "Save Changes," "Send Invitation"
- Don't use "Submit" — it says nothing about what will happen
- **Secondary button** (Cancel, Reset) should be visually subdued and positioned consistently (left of primary, or stacked below on mobile)
- Disable the submit button while submitting and show a loading indicator
- After successful submission: confirm the action ("Student added"), then navigate or reset appropriately

## Multi-Step Forms

- Show progress: step indicator ("Step 2 of 4") or progress bar
- Allow backward navigation to review and edit previous steps
- Persist data across steps — never lose progress if the user goes back
- Validate each step independently before allowing forward navigation
- Show a review/summary step before final submission for important actions
- Keep each step focused: 3–5 fields per step maximum

## Touch Considerations

- Input fields should be at least 44px tall for comfortable tapping
- Space between fields: at least 16px to prevent accidental taps on the wrong field
- Place the primary button within easy thumb reach (lower portion of the screen)
- Use native pickers (date, time, select) on mobile — they are optimized for touch
- Avoid custom dropdowns that don't respond to native scroll gestures

## Accessibility

- All fields need visible labels (not just placeholders)
- Required fields indicated with `aria-required="true"` and visible text
- Error messages associated via `aria-describedby`
- Invalid fields marked with `aria-invalid="true"`
- Focus management: after submission error, focus the first invalid field
- Form landmarks: wrap forms in `<form>` with a descriptive `aria-label` or heading
- Test with keyboard only: Tab through every field, trigger validation, submit, navigate errors
